      • generateElementProperties

        public java.util.List<ElementSequencedMergeProperty<Variable>> generateElementProperties(Variable p1,
                                                                                         Variable p2)
        Description copied from interface: SequencedMerge
        Generates a list containing the element properties. Contrary to OverallMergePropertys, they don't directly apply to the input given (being the two sequences of elements), but to elements forming the lists.
        Every time two elements are compared, a new list of properties must be generated. The reason for that is that these properties might handle different fields that depend on the constructor parameters (the two elements). Using setters instead of re-instantiating new properties is also not recommended, since a property might recursively use itself, and change the value of the elements before the end of the calculation of the result. If you are guaranteed that recursive usage will not happen, you might consider adding setters to your properties instead and always return the same list.
        Specified by:
        generateElementProperties in interface SequencedMerge<Variable>
        Parameters:
        p1 - the element from the first list to compare
        p2 - the element from the second list to compare
        Returns:
        a list of properties suiting p1 and p2

      • generateOverallProperties

        public java.util.List<OverallSequencedMergeProperty<Variable>> generateOverallProperties(java.util.List<Variable> p1,
                                                                                         java.util.List<Variable> p2)
        Description copied from interface: Merge
        Generates a list of properties from the given input.
        Every time a merge occurs, a new list of properties must be generated. The reason for that is that these properties might handle different fields that depend on the constructor parameters (the two inputs). Using setters instead of re-instantiating new properties is also not recommended, since a property might recursively use itself, and change the value of the inputs before the end of the calculation of the result. If you are guaranteed that recursive usage will not happen, you might consider adding setters to your properties instead and always return the same list.
        Specified by:
        generateOverallProperties in interface Merge<java.util.List<Variable>,java.util.List<Variable>,OverallSequencedMergeProperty<Variable>>
        Specified by:
        generateOverallProperties in interface SequencedMerge<Variable>
        Parameters:
        p1 - the first input
        p2 - the second input
        Returns:
        an empty list by default. In most of the cases, sequenced merges don't have any overall properties
